Europe. The CPT has consistently stressed the importance of ensuring that prison health-care services are subject to effective external oversight and that they have adequate resources. The Committee is of the view that the role of the Ministry of Health in providing external oversight of prison health care is essential. In the absence of such oversight, there is a risk that the health care provided to prisoners may not meet the required standards.
In Bulgaria, the CPT has observed that the role of the Ministry of Health in overseeing prison health care is limited. This is a matter of concern, as the Committee has received information indicating that there are serious deficiencies in the provision of health care to prisoners in Bulgarian prisons. These deficiencies include the lack of a proper system for identifying and registering prisoners with medical needs, the absence of adequate medical equipment and medicines, and the inadequate training of prison medical staff.
In view of the above, the CPT recommends that the Bulgarian authorities:
- establish a system for identifying and registering prisoners with medical needs;
- ensure that prison health-care services have adequate resources, including medical equipment and medicines;
- ensure that prison medical staff receive adequate training;
- establish a system for regular external oversight of prison health care by the Ministry of Health;
- take steps to ensure that prisoners with serious medical conditions are transferred to hospitals for appropriate treatment when necessary.”
